VCities are like siblings in a large polygamous family.
p4
aVEach one has a unique personality and is headed in a distinct direction.
p5
aVBut they all have somewhat shared origins.
p6
aVSometimes I think postcolonial cities are like the children
p7
aVof the two least-favorite wives,
p8
aVwho are constantly being asked,
p9
aV"Ah, why can't you be more like your sister?"
p10
aa(lp11
V(Laughter)
p12
aa(lp13
VThe "why" of cities is largely the same, no matter where they are:
p14
aVan advantageous location that makes trade and administration possible;
p15
aVthe potential for scalable opportunities
p16
aVfor the skilled and unskilled alike;
p17
aVa popular willingness to be in constant flux
p18
aVand, of course, resilience.
p19
aVThe "how" of cities, however, is a whole other story.
p20
aVHow are they run?
p21
aVHow do they grow?
p22
aVHow do they decide who belongs and who doesn't?
p23
aa(lp24
VLagos is my home.
p25
aVYou can always find the Nigerians
p26
aVby following the noise and the dancing, right?
p27
aa(lp28
V(Laughter)
p29
aa(lp30
VLike any major city, that place is a lot of things,
p31
aVmany of which are highly contradictory.
p32
aVOur public transportation doesn't quite work,
p33
aVso we have these privately owned bright yellow buses
p34
aVthat regularly cause accidents.
p35
aVLuxury car showrooms line badly maintained and often flooded roads.
p36
aVStreet evangelism is only slightly less ubiquitous
p37
aVthan street harassment.
p38
aVSex workers sometimes have two degrees, a bank job
p39
aVand a prominent role in church.
p40
aa(lp41
V(Laughter)
p42
aa(lp43
VOn any given day,
p44
aVthere can be either a party or a burned body
p45
aVin the middle of a street.
p46
aa(lp47
VThere is so much that is possible in Lagos
p48
aVand so much that isn't,
p49
aVand very often the difference between possibility and impossibility
p50
aVis simply who you are,
p51
aVand if you're lucky enough, who you're connected to.
p52
aVBelonging in Lagos is a fluid concept
p53
aVdetermined by ethnic origin, sexual orientation, gender,
p54
aVbut most visibly and often most violently,
p55
aVclass.
p56
aa(lp57
VBefore Nigeria became a country,
p58
aVfisherpeople from the inland creeks started to come down the Lagos lagoon
p59
aVand establish villages along the coast.
p60
aVAbout 60 years later, my grandfather, Oludotun Adekunle Kukoyi,
p61
aValso arrived in Lagos.
p62
aVLike me, he was an alumnus of the University of Ibadan,
p63
aVa young member of the educated elite in the independence era.
p64
aVOver time, he built an illustrious career as a land surveyor,
p65
aVmapping out now-bustling neighborhoods
p66
aVwhen they were just waist-high wild grass.
p67
aVHe died when I was nine.
p68
aVAnd by that time, my family, like the families of those fisherpeople,
p69
aVknew Lagos as home.
p70
aa(lp71
VAmong the Yoruba, we have a saying,
p72
aV"Èkó gb\u2019olè, ó gb\u2019\u1ecd\u0300l\u1eb9,"
p73
aVwhich can be translated to mean that Lagos will welcome anyone.
p74
aVBut that saying is becoming less and less true.
p75
aVMany Lagosians, including the descendants of those fisherpeople
p76
aVwho arrived generations before my grandfather,
p77
aVare now being pushed out
p78
aVto make room for an emergent city
p79
aVthat has been described as "the new Dubai."
p80
aVYou see, Lagos inspires big dreams, even in its leaders,
p81
aVand successive governments have declared aspirations
p82
aVtowards a megacity where poverty does not exist.
p83
aVUnfortunately, instead of focusing on the eradication of poverty
p84
aVas you would expect,
p85
aVthe strategy of choice focuses on eliminating the poor.
p86
aa(lp87
VLast October, the Governor announced plans
p88
aVto demolish every single waterfront settlement in Lagos.
p89
aVThere are more than 40 of these indigenous communities
p90
aVall over the city,
p91
aVwith over 300,000 people living in them.
p92
aVOtodo Gbame,
p93
aVa hundred-year-old fishing village
p94
aVwith a population about three-quarters that of Monaco
p95
aVand similar potential for beachfront luxury \u2014
p96
aa(lp97
V(Laughter)
p98
aa(lp99
Vwas one of the first to be targeted.
p100
aa(lp101
VI first heard of Otodo Gbame after the demolition started.
p102
aVWhen I visited in November 2016, I met Magdalene Aiyefoju.
p103
aVShe is a now-homeless woman
p104
aVwhose surname means, "the world is blind."
p105
aVMagdalene's son Basil was one of over 20 people
p106
aVwho were shot, drowned
p107
aVor presumed dead in that land grab.
p108
aVStanding outside her shelter, I saw the two white-sand football fields
p109
aVwhere Basil used to play.
p110
aVSpread all around us were the ruins of schools, churches,
p111
aVa primary health center, shops,
p112
aVthousands of homes.
p113
aVYoung children enthusiastically helped to put up shelters,
p114
aVand about 5,000 of the residents, with nowhere else to go,
p115
aVsimply stayed put.
p116
aVAnd then in April,
p117
aVstate security personnel came back.
p118
aVThis time, they cleared the community out completely,
p119
aVwith beatings, bullets and fire.
p120
aVAs I speak, there are construction crews preparing Otodo Gbame's beaches
p121
aVfor anyone who can afford a multi-million-dollar view.
p122
aVThe new development is called "Periwinkle Estate."
p123
aa(lp124
VForced evictions are incredibly violent and, of course, unconstitutional.
p125
aVAnd yet, they happen so often in so many of our cities,
p126
aVbecause the first thing we are taught to forget about poor people
p127
aVis that they are people.
p128
aVWe believe that a home is a thing a person absolutely has a right to,
p129
aVunless the person is poor and the home is built a certain way
p130
aVin a certain neighborhood.
p131
aVBut there is no single definition of the word "home."
p132
aVAfter all, what is a slum besides an organic response
p133
aVto acute housing deficits and income inequality?
p134
aVAnd what is a shanty if not a person making a home for themselves
p135
aVagainst all odds?
p136
aVSlums are an imperfect housing solution,
p137
aVbut they are also prime examples of the innovation, adaptability
p138
aVand resilience at the foundation \u2014
p139
aVand the heart \u2014
p140
aVof every functional city.
p141
aVYou don't need to be the new Dubai
p142
aVwhen you're already Lagos.
p143
