V(Applause)
p145
aa(lp146
VWe have our own identity,
p147
aVour own rhythm,
p148
aVand as anyone who knows Lagos can tell you,
p149
aVpoor Lagosians are very often the source of the city's character.
p150
aVWithout its poor, Lagos would not be known for its music
p151
aVor its endless energy
p152
aVor even the fact that you can buy an ice cold drink or a puppy
p153
aVthrough your car window.
p154
aa(lp155
V(Laughter)
p156
aa(lp157
VThe conditions that cause us to define certain neighborhoods as slums
p158
aVcan be effectively improved,
p159
aVbut not without recognizing the humanity and the agency
p160
aVof the people living in them.
p161
aVIn Lagos, where public goods are rarely publicly available,
p162
aVslum dwellers are often at the forefront of innovating solutions.
p163
aVAfter being disconnected from the grid for months
p164
aVbecause the power company couldn't figure out how to collect bills,
p165
aVone settlement designed a system that collectivized remittances
p166
aVand got everyone cheaper rates into the bargain.
p167
aVAnother settlement created a reform program
p168
aVthat hires local bad boys as security.
p169
aVThey know every trick and every hideout,
p170
aVso now troublemakers are more likely to get caught and reported to police
p171
aVand fewer of the youth end up engaging in criminal activity.
p172
aVYet another settlement recently completed
p173
aVa flood-safe, eco-friendly communal toilet system.
p174
aVModels like these are being adopted across Lagos.
p175
aa(lp176
VInformal settlements are incorrectly named as the problem.
p177
aVIn fact, the real problems are the factors that create them,
p178
aVlike the entrenchment of poverty,
p179
aVsocial exclusion
p180
aVand state failures.
p181
aVWhen our governments frame slums as threats
p182
aVin order to justify violent land grabs or forced evictions,
p183
aVthey're counting on those of us who live in formal housing
p184
aVto tacitly and ignorantly agree with them.
p185
aVRather, we must remind them
p186
aVthat governments exist to serve not only those who build
p187
aVand live in luxury homes,
p188
aVbut also those who clean and guard them.
p189
aVOur \u2014
p190
aa(lp191
V(Applause)
p192
aa(lp193
Vour realities may differ,
p194
aVbut our rights don't.
p195
aa(lp196
VThe Lagos state government,
p197
aVlike far too many on our continent,
p198
aVpays lip service to ideas of inclusion,
p199
aVwhile acting as though progress can only be achieved
p200
aVby the erasure, exploitation and even elimination of groups
p201
aVit considers expendable.
p202
aVPeople living with disabilities who hawk or beg on Lagos streets
p203
aVare rounded up, extorted
p204
aVand detained.
p205
aVWomen in low-income neighborhoods are picked up
p206
aVand charged with prostitution,
p207
aVregardless of what they actually do for a living.
p208
aVGay citizens are scapegoated to distract from real political problems.
p209
aVBut people, like cities, are resilient,
p210
aVand no amount of legislation or intimidation or violence
p211
aVcan fully eliminate any of us.
p212
aVProstitutes, women and women who work as prostitutes
p213
aVstill haven't gone extinct,
p214
aVdespite centuries of active suppression.
p215
aVQueer Africans continue to exist,
p216
aVeven though queerness is now criminalized in most parts of the continent.
p217
aVAnd I'm fairly certain that poor people don't generally tend to just disappear
p218
aVbecause they've been stripped of everything they have.
p219
aa(lp220
VWe are all already here,
p221
aVand that answers the question
p222
aVof whether or not we belong.
p223
aa(lp224
VWhen those fisherpeople started to sail down the lagoon
p225
aVin search of new homes,
p226
aVit could not have occurred to them
p227
aVthat the city that would rise up around them
p228
aVwould one day insist that they do not belong in it.
p229
aVI like to believe that my grandfather,
p230
aVin mapping new frontiers for Lagos,
p231
aVwas trying to open it up
p232
aVto make room for other people to be welcomed by the city
p233
aVin the same way that he was.
p234
aVOn my way here, my grandma called me
p235
aVto remind me how proud she was,
p236
aVhow proud [my grandfather] and my mother would have been.
p237
aVI am their dreams come true.
p238
aVBut there is no reason why their dreams \u2014 or mine, for that matter \u2014
p239
aVare allowed to come true
p240
aVwhile those of others are turned to nightmares.
p241
aVAnd lest we forget:
p242
aVthe minimum requirement for a dream
p243
aVis a safe place to lay your head.
p244
aa(lp245
VIt is too late now for Basil,
p246
aVbut not for Magdalene,
p247
aVnot for the hundreds of thousands,
p248
aVthe millions still under threat in Lagos
p249
aVor any of our cities.
p250
aVThe world does not have to remain blind
p251
aVto the suffering that is created when we deny people's humanity,
p252
aVor even to the incredible potential for growth that exists
p253
aVwhen we recognize and value all contributions.
p254
aa(lp255
VWe must hold our governments
p256
aVand ourselves
p257
aVaccountable
p258
aVfor keeping our shared cities safe for everyone in them,
p259
aVbecause the only cities worth building \u2014
p260
aVindeed, the only futures worth dreaming of \u2014
p261
aVare those that include all of us,
p262
aVno matter who we are
p263
aVor how we make homes for ourselves.
p264
aa(lp265
VThank you.
